It is actually a 10/21 + 2dmg.<br>
<br>
I know this from parsing tons of fight (&gt; 1000 mobs) from lvl 1 to 40 with the hammer. My modal damage, the number that appeared most often, before 28 was in fact 22. This would be expected from the common formula for modal weapon dmg (dmg * 2 + bonus). In this case my lvl based primary hand bonus ((lvl - 25) / 3) is 0, but the 2 disease dmg is applied to every hit.<br>
<br>
As my lvls went up high enough to have a lvl based damage bonus, my modal hit increased by 1 every 3 lvls as expected, but remained 2 above normal. This is a direct result of the 2 disease dmg. If the hammer instead performed as a 12/21, we would have expected to see a modal hit of 24, increasing at 28 and every 3 levels after.<br>
<br>
To accurately predict the performance of a weapon with +dmg, add it to your hit bonus, not the weapon damage. To answer the posters question, a JM does in fact outdamage a Fungus Hammer, but not by a huge margin, and both outdamage a GSC in the mainhand.<br>
<br>
Im not sure if the effect is the same for bane damage, but I believe it is. Thus if you have a 12/20 hammer, and a 0/20 +12 bane, you would expect one to hit for 24+dmg bonus, and the other to just hit for 12 + dmg bonus.<br>
